WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
[Unknown]: I.V.M.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:48.980
[Amit Varma]: I.V.M.

00:00:48.980 --> 00:00:54.980
[Amit Varma]: I.V.M.

00:00:54.980 --> 00:01:00.220
[Amit Varma]: with, a kitchen knife. A kitchen knife can also be used to kill people. It can't quite

00:01:00.220 --> 00:01:05.020
[Amit Varma]: destroy an entire neighborhood, but you can take a life or two or three.

00:01:05.020 --> 00:01:10.200
[Amit Varma]: My second question to you is, should the knife be banned? I rather suspect that I have the

00:01:10.200 --> 00:01:14.820
[Amit Varma]: same answer to these two questions as most of you do. On the question of the bombzooka,

00:01:14.820 --> 00:01:19.040
[Amit Varma]: the weapon that costs a thousand rupees and can blow up a neighborhood, yes, I believe

00:01:19.040 --> 00:01:23.380
[Amit Varma]: the government should ban it. On the question of the knife, which is so useful to us, even

00:01:23.380 --> 00:01:28.660
[Amit Varma]: essential to us in so many ways, no, I don't believe a knife should be banned. Ban the

00:01:28.660 --> 00:01:34.120
[Amit Varma]: bombzooka, don't ban the knife. But this now brings me to my third question for you. If

00:01:34.120 --> 00:01:38.980
[Amit Varma]: the bombzooka and the ordinary kitchen knife are part of a continuum in terms of the damage

00:01:38.980 --> 00:01:43.900
[Amit Varma]: they cause, somewhere in that continuum is a line that we draw in terms of whether we

00:01:43.900 --> 00:01:52.060
[Amit Varma]: ban it or not. Where do we draw that line? And why do we draw that line there?

00:01:52.060 --> 00:01:57.460
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:01:57.460 --> 00:02:03.220
[Unknown]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Badma.

00:02:03.220 --> 00:02:06.560
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen. I hope you had time to think about that third question

00:02:06.560 --> 00:02:11.700
[Amit Varma]: I asked. In case you haven't, pause this episode and think about it for a moment. Where do

00:02:11.700 --> 00:02:15.900
[Amit Varma]: you draw the line between the kitchen knife and the bombzooka and decide that a weapon

00:02:15.900 --> 00:02:21.100
[Amit Varma]: should be banned? My answer is that we draw the line depending on how much damage a weapon

00:02:21.100 --> 00:02:24.980
[Amit Varma]: can cause. With a knife, you can kill at most two or three people before you are stopped,

00:02:24.980 --> 00:02:29.580
[Amit Varma]: perhaps even less. With a bombzooka, you can kill hundreds of people, even thousands in

00:02:29.580 --> 00:02:34.240
[Amit Varma]: a crowded neighborhood or a mall or a marketplace. Where would I draw a line in between? Among

00:02:34.240 --> 00:02:39.780
[Amit Varma]: potential weapons that exist at the moment, I would draw the line at a gun. As we have

00:02:39.780 --> 00:02:43.700
[Amit Varma]: seen in recent years, it takes one nutcase to pick up a gun and go on a killing spree

00:02:43.700 --> 00:02:50.060
[Amit Varma]: that can kill 10, 20, 30 people. Also, guns are widely used by people to kill themselves

00:02:50.060 --> 00:02:55.340
[Amit Varma]: as they're an easy, relatively friction-free way to commit suicide. So I draw the line

00:02:55.340 --> 00:03:00.500
[Amit Varma]: there. And I'd argue for the status quo in India where you cannot buy a gun off the counter.

00:03:00.500 --> 00:03:06.420
[Amit Varma]: Now, it might seem odd to you that a libertarian like me holds such a position. After all,

00:03:06.420 --> 00:03:11.620
[Amit Varma]: libertarians in the USA argue vociferously for gun rights. Well, yeah, but I'd argue

00:03:11.620 --> 00:03:16.660
[Amit Varma]: that there is context there in terms of how the USA evolved, the distrust of the state

00:03:16.660 --> 00:03:21.260
[Amit Varma]: that is embedded in their culture as it should be in every culture, in fact, and that context

00:03:21.260 --> 00:03:27.180
[Amit Varma]: doesn't quite apply to India. Also, my friend and a frequent guest on the show, Shruti Rajgopalan,

00:03:27.180 --> 00:03:31.300
[Amit Varma]: once drew a two by two matrix for me on a piece of paper and showed me two kinds of

00:03:31.300 --> 00:03:36.660
[Amit Varma]: equilibria. In one equilibrium, criminals plus cops have guns and so do common citizens

00:03:36.660 --> 00:03:42.460
[Amit Varma]: to defend themselves. In another, neither criminals plus cops nor common citizens have

00:03:42.460 --> 00:03:47.860
[Amit Varma]: guns. The other two possibilities are situations where cops and criminals have guns, but citizens

00:03:47.860 --> 00:03:52.580
[Amit Varma]: don't to defend themselves. And citizens have guns, but cops don't. The argument could be

00:03:52.580 --> 00:03:58.660
[Amit Varma]: made that both of these are unstable situations, and you need to be in one of two equilibria.

00:03:58.660 --> 00:04:03.980
[Amit Varma]: Either everyone can have a gun or no one has a gun. The USA is in the first equilibrium,

00:04:03.980 --> 00:04:08.660
[Amit Varma]: India is in the second. And while I don't have enough knowledge to take a position on

00:04:08.660 --> 00:04:14.620
[Amit Varma]: the US equilibrium, I believe that India needs to stay in the second one. So my position

00:04:14.620 --> 00:04:19.460
[Amit Varma]: that the sale of guns should not be legal applies to India for now, which is the society

00:04:19.460 --> 00:04:25.580
[Amit Varma]: I live in and know and think I understand. So I speak in this context alone. Now my guests

00:04:25.580 --> 00:04:30.440
[Amit Varma]: in the show are two men who have both studied law and economics, and they both disagree

00:04:30.440 --> 00:04:36.980
[Amit Varma]: with me in different subtle ways. Shubho Roy is a fellow at the NIPFP. Sudhanshu Neema

00:04:36.980 --> 00:04:41.420
[Amit Varma]: works at the Center for Civil Society. In the conversation you're about to listen to

00:04:41.420 --> 00:04:46.740
[Amit Varma]: both of them are going to make great arguments against the position I just outlined. They

00:04:46.740 --> 00:04:51.660
[Amit Varma]: might convince me or they might not. But before we go to the conversation, let's take a quick

00:04:51.660 --> 00:04:57.460
[Amit Varma]: commercial break. Like me, are you someone who loves fine art, but can't really afford

00:04:57.460 --> 00:05:01.700
[Amit Varma]: to have paintings by the artists you like hanging on your walls? Well, worry no more.

00:05:01.700 --> 00:05:06.500
[Amit Varma]: Head on over to Indian colors.com. Indian colors is a company that licenses images of

00:05:06.500 --> 00:05:11.420
[Amit Varma]: the finest modern art from some of the best artists in India and adapts them into objects

00:05:11.420 --> 00:05:17.020
[Amit Varma]: of everyday use. These include wearable art like stoles and shrugs, home decor like cushion

00:05:17.020 --> 00:05:21.740
[Amit Varma]: covers and table runners and accessories like tote bags. This allows art lovers to actually

00:05:21.740 --> 00:05:26.940
[Amit Varma]: get fine art into their homes at an accessible price. And artists get royalties on sales

00:05:26.940 --> 00:05:31.940
[Amit Varma]: just like authors do. What's more, Indian colors now has an exciting range of new products,

00:05:31.940 --> 00:05:36.340
[Amit Varma]: including fridge magnets with some stunning motifs and salad bowls and platters made of

00:05:36.340 --> 00:05:41.460
[Amit Varma]: mango wood. Their artists include luminaries like Babu Xavier, Vazvo, Ex Vazvo, Brinda

00:05:41.460 --> 00:05:46.340
[Amit Varma]: Miller, Dilip Sharma, Shruti Nelson and Pradeep Mishra. They accept bulk orders for corporate

00:05:46.340 --> 00:05:50.520
[Amit Varma]: and festival gifting. But even if you want to buy just for yourself or a friend, head

00:05:50.520 --> 00:05:55.860
[Amit Varma]: on over to Indian colors.com. That's colors with an OU. And if you want a 20% discount,

00:05:55.860 --> 00:06:02.660
[Amit Varma]: apply the code IBM 20. That's IBM for IBM podcast IBM 20 for a 20% discount at Indian

00:06:02.660 --> 00:06:08.580
[Amit Varma]: colors.com. Shubho, welcome to the scene and the unseen. Thank you, Amit. So Shubho, tell

00:06:08.580 --> 00:06:13.660
[Guest 1]: me I mean, what's your answer to the three questions I posed? I would like to squirm

00:06:13.660 --> 00:06:20.060
[Guest 1]: around and say the question of banning is a very simplistic understanding of how law

00:06:20.060 --> 00:06:26.540
[Guest 1]: operates. You would argue that the Indian Army should have the bomb Zuka. And that goes

00:06:26.540 --> 00:06:31.820
[Guest 1]: on to say, for example, nuclear weapons, which is correct. But at the end of the day, if

00:06:31.820 --> 00:06:36.780
[Guest 1]: you take a nuclear weapon, bomb Zuka, or some of the weapons that are there, while it is

00:06:36.780 --> 00:06:42.140
[Guest 1]: licensed, it's at the end of the day in the hand of one individual, somebody in the army,

00:06:42.140 --> 00:06:45.420
[Guest 1]: somebody in the Air Force, or maybe a group of people in the Air Force or army when it

00:06:45.420 --> 00:06:51.020
[Guest 1]: comes to nukes, because we keep them disassembled, have the system to launch and destroy. And

00:06:51.020 --> 00:06:56.580
[Guest 1]: those are individual citizens of India who have access to weapons of mass destruction.

00:06:56.580 --> 00:07:00.540
[Guest 1]: Yes, they have joined the army, but we should not think that the army has complete control

00:07:00.540 --> 00:07:07.980
[Guest 1]: all the time. And on the other hand, on the knife, if you gave a knife to a three year

00:07:07.980 --> 00:07:13.060
[Guest 1]: old child or a five year old child, or your child, you would be put away for child endangerment

00:07:13.060 --> 00:07:17.420
[Guest 1]: in any society. So you see, at both ends, there are exceptions. And we should start

00:07:17.420 --> 00:07:23.060
[Guest 1]: thinking about from this context that the context of ban, absolute clear ban is kind

00:07:23.060 --> 00:07:28.300
[Guest 1]: of extreme in law and usually does not serve our purpose. And that is why, for example,

00:07:28.300 --> 00:07:33.100
[Guest 1]: we have legislatures to debate these issues multiple number of times and come with graded

00:07:33.100 --> 00:07:39.020
[Guest 1]: intervention. So even a knife to a child is illegal, and you should go to jail for child

00:07:39.020 --> 00:07:43.740
[Guest 1]: endangerment if you leave a large number, let your child play with knives. And on the

00:07:43.740 --> 00:07:50.660
[Guest 1]: other hand, even a bomb Zuka is not illegal in the hands of a fighter pilot or soldier,

00:07:50.660 --> 00:07:56.820
[Guest 1]: or somebody who has been licensed and carry has the power to do that. And those person

00:07:56.820 --> 00:08:02.220
[Guest 1]: could still go on rampage, but we have created systems and processes hopefully to prevent

00:08:02.220 --> 00:08:06.900
[Guest 1]: that. And so these are the two extremes, but at neither extremes, do you get a clear ban

00:08:06.900 --> 00:08:07.900
[Amit Varma]: or a clear allowance?

00:08:07.900 --> 00:08:12.540
[Amit Varma]: I think when I use the term ban, I mean, these would be commonly understood exceptions. I

00:08:12.540 --> 00:08:16.260
[Amit Varma]: mean, everybody gets it that okay, the army is going to have weapons and you can't give

00:08:16.260 --> 00:08:22.300
[Amit Varma]: weapons or even anything that could potentially be used as a weapon to a child. So these are

00:08:22.300 --> 00:08:27.100
[Amit Varma]: kind of understood and also the fact that the army has these weapons and it consists

00:08:27.100 --> 00:08:34.060
[Amit Varma]: of individuals who could also have homicidal urges and go berserk is not really an argument

00:08:34.060 --> 00:08:39.180
[Amit Varma]: for letting everybody have them right because the probabilities rise exponentially if you

00:08:39.180 --> 00:08:40.420
[Amit Varma]: let the common citizenry.

00:08:40.420 --> 00:08:42.340
[Guest 1]: True. So all I'm saying is that there's a grading.

00:08:42.340 --> 00:08:43.340
[Amit Varma]: I get that.

00:08:43.340 --> 00:08:47.660
[Guest 1]: And in that grading once I think now I would argue that the guns come in somewhere in that

00:08:47.660 --> 00:08:52.220
[Guest 1]: grading where in the Indian context, we have kind of done it very dumb, that we have done

00:08:52.220 --> 00:08:57.180
[Guest 1]: it very simply and said ban. Instead of that, I would say you do grading for similarly for

00:08:57.180 --> 00:09:01.660
[Guest 1]: guns and the guns fall in that continuum and depending on the usage of the gun, depending

00:09:01.660 --> 00:09:06.180
[Guest 1]: on who has the gun, you do the systems and as you pointed out correctly that the American

00:09:06.180 --> 00:09:11.940
[Guest 1]: system is one end of it, no licensing, no registration. But the Indian system is at

00:09:11.940 --> 00:09:17.580
[Guest 1]: the other extreme of it, that unless some civil servant is convinced that your life

00:09:17.580 --> 00:09:26.100
[Guest 1]: is in danger, you cannot purchase a gun. It is not a judicial process. It is not a process

00:09:26.100 --> 00:09:31.220
[Guest 1]: which is subject to review in the normal system that we understand it. You don't get a reasoned

00:09:31.220 --> 00:09:36.580
[Guest 1]: order as to whether your life is in, why your life is not in danger when you apply for it.

00:09:36.580 --> 00:09:41.900
[Guest 1]: So it creates a large amount of discretion to that entity which gives you the license.

00:09:41.900 --> 00:09:46.660
[Guest 1]: So we do not have a situation where as you pointed out, nobody has guns. We have a large

00:09:46.660 --> 00:09:52.700
[Guest 1]: number of guns in the Indian system floating around. So the interesting statistics here

00:09:52.700 --> 00:09:59.420
[Guest 1]: is that there are about 97 lakh registered guns in India, which is one per hundred.

00:09:59.420 --> 00:10:02.820
[Amit Varma]: I didn't know that. That's a lot of guns.

00:10:02.820 --> 00:10:10.060
[Guest 1]: Wait, there are around 7.1 crore total guns in India, which gives you a number of five

00:10:10.060 --> 00:10:15.220
[Guest 1]: per hundred. US is the other extreme just for context is 120 per hundred, but there

00:10:15.220 --> 00:10:20.020
[Guest 1]: are many countries above us. So what we get is around 6 crore guns in this country, which

00:10:20.020 --> 00:10:26.220
[Guest 1]: are unregistered. And these people who own them, not all of them are criminals or horrible

00:10:26.220 --> 00:10:30.020
[Guest 1]: people. But because we have created this extreme ban, there are a large number of people who

00:10:30.020 --> 00:10:34.180
[Guest 1]: have guns because they've inherited it or when the law came in, they had the power to

00:10:34.180 --> 00:10:38.460
[Guest 1]: hold guns. They didn't hand it over because they didn't want to or for whatever reasons.

00:10:38.460 --> 00:10:42.460
[Guest 1]: And now they're completely criminalized. If they even come willingly to hand over the

00:10:42.460 --> 00:10:47.700
[Guest 1]: guns, they are open to prosecution under the Arms Act, which carries seven years of imprisonment

00:10:47.700 --> 00:10:50.700
[Guest 1]: and which is very dangerous because it's not even a compoundable offense that you can go

00:10:50.700 --> 00:10:54.180
[Guest 1]: and say, look, I'm willingly gave up my gun. So please don't prosecute me. You're totally

00:10:54.180 --> 00:10:59.060
[Guest 1]: at the mercy. And this point is very interesting. We have a gun to population ratio of five

00:10:59.060 --> 00:11:03.540
[Guest 1]: guns per hundred people, not that gun free as we think India is.

00:11:03.540 --> 00:11:09.180
[Amit Varma]: So I have a couple of points to make here, questions to ask rather. One is that it is

00:11:09.180 --> 00:11:13.300
[Amit Varma]: implied in the statistic that listen, actually, it's not that hard to get a gun in India,

00:11:13.300 --> 00:11:18.340
[Amit Varma]: you can and I understand that, that you can if you want go out in the black market and

00:11:18.340 --> 00:11:21.860
[Amit Varma]: figure out a way to get a gun. But there is a transaction cost, you have to make a certain

00:11:21.860 --> 00:11:26.940
[Amit Varma]: amount of effort, not everyone does that. And so, you know, it is much harder for you

00:11:26.940 --> 00:11:32.300
[Amit Varma]: to get hold of a gun on impulse, whereas otherwise, you know, you could just take it out of your

00:11:32.300 --> 00:11:39.220
[Amit Varma]: pocket. Also, the point is that a lot of gun killings, a lot of gun deaths rather that

00:11:39.220 --> 00:11:44.340
[Amit Varma]: happen, even in the US are not sort of shootouts we see in the news, they could be domestic

00:11:44.340 --> 00:11:48.780
[Amit Varma]: disputes and very often and this is a huge problem, they are suicides, there happens

00:11:48.780 --> 00:11:53.420
[Amit Varma]: to be a gun in the house. And again, a gun is an easy way to commit suicide on an impulse,

00:11:53.420 --> 00:11:56.660
[Amit Varma]: you can take a gun, put it at your head and press the trigger. And that happens a lot

00:11:56.660 --> 00:12:02.660
[Amit Varma]: apparently. And it's much harder to actually go to a bridge and jump off or hang yourself

00:12:02.660 --> 00:12:08.780
[Amit Varma]: with all the elaborate apparatus that involves and the fact that there's a little more effort

00:12:08.780 --> 00:12:13.420
[Amit Varma]: involved in that makes it a little less unlikely. So I mean, I've kind of made two separate

00:12:13.420 --> 00:12:15.460
[Amit Varma]: points, what do you feel about them?

00:12:15.460 --> 00:12:21.460
[Guest 1]: So on the point that it is a little difficult to get it and makes it difficult for impulse

00:12:21.460 --> 00:12:27.780
[Guest 1]: buyers to get it, I agree with you there. But if you had a fairly robust registration

00:12:27.780 --> 00:12:33.380
[Guest 1]: system, where there was no discretion on that part, like whether you are facing a threat

00:12:33.380 --> 00:12:37.220
[Guest 1]: or not, but there is still objective checks that you don't have any previous criminal

00:12:37.220 --> 00:12:43.020
[Guest 1]: convictions, you don't have domestic violence complaints against you, you do not have XYZ

00:12:43.020 --> 00:12:46.980
[Guest 1]: things against you're not on parole or something like that, or you're not being charged and

00:12:46.980 --> 00:12:52.460
[Guest 1]: tried, you can create those checks and balances to make it a little more difficult to make

00:12:52.460 --> 00:12:58.540
[Guest 1]: impulse buys. And it still allows people but once you have made a purchase, you're not

00:12:58.540 --> 00:13:03.340
[Guest 1]: completely criminalized. Today, if you are under stress or think that something bad will

00:13:03.340 --> 00:13:07.260
[Guest 1]: happen, you buy the gun and now you're a criminal forever. So now you have to hide it, you have

00:13:07.260 --> 00:13:12.700
[Guest 1]: to be unsafe about it. But on the other hand, if you did that all of that and for example,

00:13:12.700 --> 00:13:19.620
[Guest 1]: do a seven day gun safety course, go and do a medical checkup, go and get a NOC from your

00:13:19.620 --> 00:13:23.160
[Guest 1]: wife, spouse or anybody who's living with you at home. These are some of the systems

00:13:23.160 --> 00:13:27.820
[Guest 1]: which other countries do, which sometimes when we look from India seems like a ban,

00:13:27.820 --> 00:13:32.740
[Guest 1]: like Canada does it you have to get a psychiatric checkup before you get it and they talk to

00:13:32.740 --> 00:13:36.500
[Guest 1]: you and they check that you're not there your family has to people living with you have

00:13:36.500 --> 00:13:41.460
[Guest 1]: to give an approval or no objection. And then you get it and that allows for example, to

00:13:41.460 --> 00:13:49.060
[Guest 1]: take care of the first problem, which is the impulse buys. On suicide, I think yes and

00:13:49.060 --> 00:13:55.100
[Guest 1]: no to that extent. There are many other ways to go and they are very painful. And if you

00:13:55.100 --> 00:13:59.540
[Guest 1]: are a libertarian, you would argue if you want to finish off your life, it is your life.

00:13:59.540 --> 00:14:04.220
[Guest 1]: I don't subscribe to that point of view. But I think suicide is a mental health problem.

00:14:04.220 --> 00:14:09.380
[Guest 1]: And there are reasons for suicide. Japan has the highest suicide rate in the world in the

00:14:09.380 --> 00:14:14.940
[Guest 1]: developed world, not much access to guns, people are putting themselves out with carbon

00:14:14.940 --> 00:14:21.200
[Guest 1]: dioxide with a lot of other jumping off buildings. So when you have a suicide epidemic in a country,

00:14:21.200 --> 00:14:25.420
[Guest 1]: you should start looking at what are the cultural reasons which cause it, I think the US is

00:14:25.420 --> 00:14:30.660
[Guest 1]: also going through some problems which create the suicide epidemic that you see in the US.

00:14:30.660 --> 00:14:37.260
[Guest 1]: I think it is the retrenchment of the workforce, which is not in the knowledge economy as production

00:14:37.260 --> 00:14:43.220
[Guest 1]: goes out. And you know, JD Vance writes interesting things about why we are getting this problem

00:14:43.220 --> 00:14:50.900
[Guest 1]: in the US because even mass shootouts are fairly recent phenomena in the US 80s 90s.

00:14:50.900 --> 00:14:56.140
[Guest 1]: They had guns for hundreds of years, 1776 onwards, they have been owning guns, we didn't

00:14:56.140 --> 00:15:01.460
[Guest 1]: have this problem, we have some deep cultural problems there. Similarly, what we have in

00:15:01.460 --> 00:15:05.820
[Guest 1]: Japan probably, which leads to suicide. So we have to start thinking about that point

00:15:05.820 --> 00:15:11.860
[Guest 1]: that yes, self harm is a problem with guns. There are a lot of ways to go out yourself

00:15:11.860 --> 00:15:16.420
[Guest 1]: and there I agree. But that is still from a libertarian point of view. That's not a

00:15:16.420 --> 00:15:22.460
[Guest 1]: good argument. Because if you will harm yourself, for that people who don't harm themselves

00:15:22.460 --> 00:15:26.740
[Guest 1]: should not leak. One of the easiest ways carbon monoxide poisoning, just turn your exhaust,

00:15:26.740 --> 00:15:28.700
[Amit Varma]: put a pipe in your exhaust and put it in your car.

00:15:28.700 --> 00:15:31.940
[Amit Varma]: Sure, that's fair enough. And the one point where you've got me is a libertarian point

00:15:31.940 --> 00:15:34.860
[Amit Varma]: of view where I do believe that if you have the right to life, you have the right to kill

00:15:34.860 --> 00:15:38.540
[Amit Varma]: yourself. And I also believe that suicide is not necessarily a mental health problem.

00:15:38.540 --> 00:15:43.540
[Amit Varma]: It can, under certain circumstances be quite rational to choose to go out. So I buy that

00:15:43.540 --> 00:15:47.780
[Amit Varma]: part of it. And that's a separate argument entirely, really. But the consequentialist

00:15:47.780 --> 00:15:51.980
[Amit Varma]: argument against guns would involve that suicide rates go up and however high the Japanese

00:15:51.980 --> 00:15:56.100
[Amit Varma]: rate might be, we don't know the counterfactual or what it would have been if guns were more

00:15:56.100 --> 00:16:01.100
[Amit Varma]: freely available. But we have and I'll come to this a little later when Sudhanshu also

00:16:01.100 --> 00:16:05.220
[Amit Varma]: joins the discussion, perhaps that though I'm waiting for you to kind of let's squeeze

00:16:05.220 --> 00:16:10.780
[Amit Varma]: this argument dry. But you know, the experience in Australia, for example, after they did

00:16:10.780 --> 00:16:15.100
[Amit Varma]: their gun buyback, and they changed their gun laws, is that there are multiple studies

00:16:15.100 --> 00:16:19.300
[Amit Varma]: we show which are which I'll cite, we showed that the rates of suicides drastically went

00:16:19.300 --> 00:16:24.780
[Amit Varma]: down. Obviously, it's not a magic bullet, if I may use that phrase, but we'll come to

00:16:24.780 --> 00:16:30.380
[Amit Varma]: that. I also wanted to address what you sort of said about, okay, here's what we can do

00:16:30.380 --> 00:16:34.300
[Amit Varma]: with guns, you are not arguing they should be just sold over the counter, like random

00:16:34.300 --> 00:16:39.580
[Amit Varma]: medicines, like an aspirin or something, but that they should be licensing. I have sort

00:16:39.580 --> 00:16:47.740
[Amit Varma]: of two points to make. One is that we don't really have state capacity in India for anything.

00:16:47.740 --> 00:16:50.900
[Amit Varma]: So if you're going to say that these are the check, like if I want to buy a gun, these

00:16:50.900 --> 00:16:55.660
[Amit Varma]: are the checks and balances. Number one, there isn't that state capacity to make sure I jump

00:16:55.660 --> 00:17:00.420
[Amit Varma]: through all those hoops. So the system will be perverted in some way, like for example,

00:17:00.420 --> 00:17:05.260
[Amit Varma]: today, you can go to the RTO and get a driving license without actually taking the test.

00:17:05.260 --> 00:17:09.820
[Amit Varma]: And I've seen that happen enough. And that's a failure of state capacity and failure of

00:17:09.820 --> 00:17:15.220
[Amit Varma]: state capacity is essentially ubiquitous everywhere except when it comes to pure rent seeking

00:17:15.220 --> 00:17:21.300
[Amit Varma]: when there is no lack of it. And the other issue there is that, especially with regard

00:17:21.300 --> 00:17:25.500
[Amit Varma]: to India, when state capacity is low, we have seen that any system that can be gamed will

00:17:25.500 --> 00:17:30.420
[Amit Varma]: be gamed. Right. So if you, for example, make it a requirement that okay, you have to get

00:17:30.420 --> 00:17:34.820
[Amit Varma]: a psychiatrist certificate before we get to the gun. Come on, you know, there'll be the

00:17:34.820 --> 00:17:39.220
[Amit Varma]: shop set up where an agent will get you a psychiatrist certificate and take 1000 bucks

00:17:39.220 --> 00:17:45.260
[Amit Varma]: or whatever it is. And so that's that's one objection, the state capacity objection. And

00:17:45.260 --> 00:17:50.180
[Amit Varma]: my second objection is also that look, I live in India. Okay. I mean, I've lived in India

00:17:50.180 --> 00:17:55.200
[Amit Varma]: all my life, obviously, and I'm 45. And I've never felt the need to have a gun for purposes

00:17:55.200 --> 00:18:00.500
[Amit Varma]: of self defense. Because any dicey situations that I have got myself in, I mean, I've never

00:18:00.500 --> 00:18:05.140
[Amit Varma]: seen a gun really in civil life. There's never been like a shootout where I'm like, if I

00:18:05.140 --> 00:18:11.500
[Amit Varma]: had a gun, I could intervene now. That's one that if you make guns freely available, you

00:18:11.500 --> 00:18:15.660
[Amit Varma]: might create a situation where I might feel that need, but then you would be shifting

00:18:15.660 --> 00:18:21.340
[Amit Varma]: from this equilibrium in India where nobody has guns to the sort of US equilibrium where

00:18:21.340 --> 00:18:26.660
[Amit Varma]: because anybody can get a gun, you also feel the need to get a gun to defend yourself.

00:18:26.660 --> 00:18:31.960
[Amit Varma]: And I am like, why move from this equilibrium to that one? These are sort of my two points

00:18:31.960 --> 00:18:37.620
[Guest 1]: state capacity and the equilibrium. On the question of state capacity, I would argue

00:18:37.620 --> 00:18:44.860
[Guest 1]: that lack of state capacity, if it is taken as a reason for accepting reduction of freedom,

00:18:44.860 --> 00:18:49.140
[Guest 1]: then you have to argue that it is okay for Gurgaon police to issue an advisory that women

00:18:49.140 --> 00:18:53.900
[Guest 1]: will not travel after eight o'clock, because Gurgaon police is under manned. And so they

00:18:53.900 --> 00:18:59.020
[Guest 1]: are unable to work. So that is first issue that we get that then that is a slippery slope

00:18:59.020 --> 00:19:03.380
[Guest 1]: on which you start losing a lot of things. Actually, what has happened is, because of

00:19:03.380 --> 00:19:08.840
[Guest 1]: the ban, we haven't developed state capacity. So the ban then becomes justification for

00:19:08.840 --> 00:19:13.580
[Guest 1]: not investing in state capacity. And I would say, if you give the people of a kind, if

00:19:13.580 --> 00:19:17.140
[Guest 1]: the government had the choice, you can ban it, or you can regulate it, they'll always

00:19:17.140 --> 00:19:22.660
[Guest 1]: choose ban, because then they don't have to build state capacity to do it. But because

00:19:22.660 --> 00:19:27.220
[Guest 1]: of that lack of state capacity, we already have six crore unregistered guns. So I would

00:19:27.220 --> 00:19:31.860
[Guest 1]: say that, because of that lack of state capacity, we have that problem. And I agree with you.

00:19:31.860 --> 00:19:36.780
[Guest 1]: Yes, there were problems. But for example, recently, what Delhi RTO forces, the driving

00:19:36.780 --> 00:19:41.940
[Guest 1]: instructor, one of the RTO officers to take a video of you driving. When I took the driving

00:19:41.940 --> 00:19:49.060
[Guest 1]: test recently, they had to make me take a video. And so state capacity develops. Because

00:19:49.060 --> 00:19:52.820
[Guest 1]: we could have said, okay, we'll ban driving, because we don't have state capacity for doing

00:19:52.820 --> 00:19:57.500
[Guest 1]: that. And you could say that, yes, we'll do public transport, we'll do metro and practically

00:19:57.500 --> 00:20:01.420
[Guest 1]: in Delhi, there's a very good argument to make or in Bombay that why do you need a driving

00:20:01.420 --> 00:20:06.340
[Guest 1]: license in Bombay or Delhi. That brings me to the second point about the equilibrium.

00:20:06.340 --> 00:20:12.700
[Guest 1]: I would argue that equilibrium you face is because of the places you choose to live in.

00:20:12.700 --> 00:20:17.940
[Guest 1]: I choose to live in Delhi. It has got central armed police forces, it has got Delhi police,

00:20:17.940 --> 00:20:22.820
[Guest 1]: the best police force in the country. It has got large amount of security cordons around

00:20:22.820 --> 00:20:27.500
[Guest 1]: the system. So we live under that security umbrella. But what if you are a person who

00:20:27.500 --> 00:20:34.460
[Guest 1]: stood for a panchayat election in Kashmir? What if you are a person who stood up against

00:20:34.460 --> 00:20:42.380
[Guest 1]: the Naxals in Dante Vada? Okay, or you're just the local doctor who's being harassed

00:20:42.380 --> 00:20:47.380
[Guest 1]: by goons, people who go out to the villages, people who go out to places where these 6.1

00:20:47.380 --> 00:20:51.340
[Guest 1]: crore unregistered weapons are, they are not in the same equilibrium.

00:20:51.340 --> 00:20:55.420
[Amit Varma]: In that case, the lack of state capacity supports your point, because you're saying that if

00:20:55.420 --> 00:20:59.380
[Amit Varma]: the state cannot protect me from Naxals in the village where I live, at least give me

00:20:59.380 --> 00:21:00.980
[Guest 1]: the right to protect myself.

00:21:00.980 --> 00:21:08.340
[Guest 1]: And I would say also state is always an ex-post actor. That it comes after you have been shot,

00:21:08.340 --> 00:21:12.820
[Guest 1]: it might do some justice and try to put the person in jail. If you believe in vengeance,

00:21:12.820 --> 00:21:17.140
[Guest 1]: they can put that person to death penalty also, but that person is gone. And that is

00:21:17.140 --> 00:21:23.340
[Guest 1]: taken, that is over for you. So I would always say that you should have a last line of defense.

00:21:23.340 --> 00:21:27.780
[Guest 1]: And of course, that should be done reasonably, just like we have public transport in Delhi,

00:21:27.780 --> 00:21:33.020
[Guest 1]: but I still want my car. And of course, again, I would argue that there are greater defense

00:21:33.020 --> 00:21:37.340
[Guest 1]: requirements for different people. But it is not always very narrow that you must have

00:21:37.340 --> 00:21:42.820
[Guest 1]: a threat, identified threat. For example, we allow, we have created a nice exception

00:21:42.820 --> 00:21:46.780
[Guest 1]: for parliamentarians. Parliamentarians can buy guns the moment they become parliamentarians.

00:21:46.780 --> 00:21:52.820
[Guest 1]: We don't adjust the threat of individual parliamentarians. But I would say why just parliamentarians?

00:21:52.820 --> 00:21:56.420
[Guest 1]: I think if you're a parliamentarian from Bombay or Delhi, the risk is much lower than if you

00:21:56.420 --> 00:22:01.700
[Guest 1]: just even stood for a Gram Panchayat election in Kashmir, or a headmaster in a school in

00:22:01.700 --> 00:22:08.500
[Guest 1]: Dante Wada. So you're caught in the crossfire. It's your last line of defense. And you know,

00:22:08.500 --> 00:22:16.140
[Guest 1]: 2008, the Bombay attack, it can happen in India, again and again, it was very successful.

00:22:16.140 --> 00:22:20.740
[Guest 1]: I'm surprised. And I am thankful to the Indian state for probably preventing those things

00:22:20.740 --> 00:22:25.540
[Guest 1]: from happening again and again. But 2008, I talked to somebody who said, this is a normal

00:22:25.540 --> 00:22:30.140
[Guest 1]: thing in Kashmir, holding up militants in hotels and then killing because hotels are

00:22:30.140 --> 00:22:34.500
[Guest 1]: a good target. Most people are not residents. It's a very common thing to do in Kashmir.

00:22:34.500 --> 00:22:36.660
[Guest 1]: And you were in Bombay at the time that affected you personally?

00:22:36.660 --> 00:22:39.860
[Guest 1]: No, I did not. I was not in Bombay, but I had worked with somebody who got killed in

00:22:39.860 --> 00:22:45.820
[Guest 1]: that. And yes, that kind of changed my perception on this issue. And I started reading more.

00:22:45.820 --> 00:22:51.620
[Guest 1]: And then I went from this nuanced position of from a simplistic position of ban and non

00:22:51.620 --> 00:22:57.220
[Guest 1]: ban and allowed to a more nuanced graded position. So if you are one of those people, the other

00:22:57.220 --> 00:23:03.140
[Guest 1]: thing I would say is also in this case is federalism. That you can make laws that okay,

00:23:03.140 --> 00:23:08.460
[Guest 1]: you can't have guns here, you can have guns there. But those are also options to choose

00:23:08.460 --> 00:23:11.300
[Guest 1]: for the US doesn't have a single gun law, by the way.

00:23:11.300 --> 00:23:13.300
[Amit Varma]: Oh, okay. It's all the states.

00:23:13.300 --> 00:23:17.980
[Guest 1]: States or even city specific cities can have ordinances. I think we should also think of

00:23:17.980 --> 00:23:24.460
[Guest 1]: federalism on that way. But again, what the main judgment in the US which created all

00:23:24.460 --> 00:23:30.820
[Guest 1]: this dispute was the Heller judgment, which people misquote. The Heller judgment required

00:23:30.820 --> 00:23:37.820
[Guest 1]: residents of Washington DC if they owned a gun to either disassemble the gun or an unload

00:23:37.820 --> 00:23:43.240
[Guest 1]: and disassemble the gun or keep the gun loaded and assembled with a lock physical lock and

00:23:43.240 --> 00:23:47.500
[Guest 1]: key on the trigger to prevent it from being used. And the person who wanted was a retired

00:23:47.500 --> 00:23:52.220
[Guest 1]: cop who had investigated mafia systems and he would have to keep a gun with a physical

00:23:52.220 --> 00:23:57.700
[Guest 1]: lock on the thing and he said this extreme and the US Supreme Court position is that

00:23:57.700 --> 00:24:02.620
[Guest 1]: you can't put so much restrictions on the right to bear arms that it becomes ineffective.

00:24:02.620 --> 00:24:06.820
[Guest 1]: And think of it, the Washington didn't ban it. They put so many restrictions that it

00:24:06.820 --> 00:24:11.060
[Guest 1]: became infeasible. And I think that is where we should start thinking about that. No, let's

00:24:11.060 --> 00:24:16.640
[Guest 1]: not put so much restrictions that none of us can. And I would say also there is shooting

00:24:16.640 --> 00:24:23.540
[Guest 1]: as a sport. Most of Indian top shooters people don't know this go to Germany to train or

00:24:23.540 --> 00:24:27.660
[Guest 1]: to other countries. Bindra went to Germany to train. Why? It's impossible to import a

00:24:27.660 --> 00:24:32.180
[Amit Varma]: gun in India. High quality guns cannot be imported. And also even trivial things like

00:24:32.180 --> 00:24:36.820
[Amit Varma]: the import duties on bullets and all of that nonsense even for a sportsman like him. Yeah.

00:24:36.820 --> 00:24:41.020
[Guest 1]: And things like that it made him cheaper to just go outside and practice and I think it

00:24:41.020 --> 00:24:45.860
[Guest 1]: is good to have a amount of population who are trained in firearms. So there are two

00:24:45.860 --> 00:24:50.380
[Amit Varma]: aspects to what you just said. One is there is a philosophical argument of we should have

00:24:50.380 --> 00:24:56.020
[Amit Varma]: the right to defend ourselves. And you turn my point of state capacity against me by showing

00:24:56.020 --> 00:25:00.140
[Amit Varma]: that I mean, we have privilege to be in Delhi and Bombay respectively. But if you are in

00:25:00.140 --> 00:25:04.740
[Amit Varma]: a smaller part of India where there is effectively no rule of law, and you can't tell a citizen

00:25:04.740 --> 00:25:08.780
[Amit Varma]: that the state won't defend you, but you can't defend yourself either. So that's your sort

00:25:08.780 --> 00:25:15.180
[Amit Varma]: of philosophical argument if I stated correctly. And the practical argument, if one may say

00:25:15.180 --> 00:25:20.460
[Amit Varma]: comes from the instance of the 2008 attacks, where you're saying that, listen, it is probable

00:25:20.460 --> 00:25:25.580
[Amit Varma]: that if one of the victims or one of the people who was in that space had a gun, it is somewhat

00:25:25.580 --> 00:25:30.140
[Amit Varma]: probable that the casualties could have been less because the likelihood of someone fighting

00:25:30.140 --> 00:25:34.220
[Amit Varma]: back is nonzero. And therefore they could have or at least the guards had guns. Oh,

00:25:34.220 --> 00:25:38.780
[Guest 1]: even the guard, even the guards don't have even private security in India can't get guns.

00:25:38.780 --> 00:25:43.580
[Guest 1]: At the most one guy has a smooth barrel shotgun, which is legal and all that very difficult.

00:25:43.580 --> 00:25:45.620
[Amit Varma]: Even private security guards can't have guns.

00:25:45.620 --> 00:25:49.820
[Amit Varma]: So this is an argument that people in favor of gun rights make whenever there is a mass

00:25:49.820 --> 00:25:54.900
[Amit Varma]: shooting that, you know, there were less people would have died if they were guns. So I'm

00:25:54.900 --> 00:25:59.940
[Amit Varma]: curious that you obviously have to, I mean, there is a trade off here, you have to weigh

00:25:59.940 --> 00:26:04.820
[Amit Varma]: the likelihood of the shooter being stopped before he kills so many people, with the likelihood

00:26:04.820 --> 00:26:10.380
[Amit Varma]: of more people dying in a dispersed way, including from suicides or domestic quarrels or misfires,

00:26:10.380 --> 00:26:15.460
[Amit Varma]: if a child gets it or whatever, you have to weigh those two. Are there statistics that

00:26:15.460 --> 00:26:20.300
[Amit Varma]: you can use in your favor, leaving the philosophical argument aside, just looking at consequences?

00:26:20.300 --> 00:26:23.940
[Amit Varma]: Are there statistics you can cite in your favor to show that there is a correlation

00:26:23.940 --> 00:26:28.460
[Amit Varma]: between greater availability of guns and less gun violence?

00:26:28.460 --> 00:26:33.820
[Guest 1]: No, difficult. The problem with the statistics in this is, as you pointed out, different

00:26:33.820 --> 00:26:35.820
[Amit Varma]: cultural political systems.

00:26:35.820 --> 00:26:37.500
[Amit Varma]: So the counterfactuals don't exist.

00:26:37.500 --> 00:26:44.220
[Guest 1]: Yes, but I would argue that when people say guns are banned in most developed countries,

00:26:44.220 --> 00:26:48.820
[Guest 1]: they are making a very simplistic comparison with the Indian system. And that is not true.

00:26:48.820 --> 00:26:52.940
[Guest 1]: In many developed countries, you're allowed to buy guns for home defense. Sportsmen are

00:26:52.940 --> 00:26:57.820
[Guest 1]: allowed to buy guns, you're allowed to hold guns for systems with different restrictions.

00:26:57.820 --> 00:27:02.220
[Guest 1]: And I would say many of them are far more peaceful than India is. India's homicide rates

00:27:02.220 --> 00:27:08.820
[Guest 1]: are pretty high. It's not that low as we would like to think it is. And that's my point on

00:27:08.820 --> 00:27:13.900
[Guest 1]: this issue. If we were to be able to do this, you know, kind of a calculus and come to the

00:27:13.900 --> 00:27:18.900
[Guest 1]: right point, then it doesn't work that way. It is a call you have to take. And there I

00:27:18.900 --> 00:27:24.980
[Guest 1]: would argue where is the origin of our gun law. Our gun law starts in 1878. After the

00:27:24.980 --> 00:27:30.780
[Guest 1]: mutiny, where the sole objective of the British rulers were to take away all the guns from

00:27:30.780 --> 00:27:36.580
[Guest 1]: Indians because they didn't like what happened the last time Indians had guns. And that was

00:27:36.580 --> 00:27:40.940
[Guest 1]: the philosophical basis for our gun law. People make these other arguments for that it is

00:27:40.940 --> 00:27:41.940
[Amit Varma]: not.

00:27:41.940 --> 00:27:46.660
[Amit Varma]: But the philosophical basis was an oppressive state wanting to keep its subjects in check.

00:27:46.660 --> 00:27:51.820
[Guest 1]: Yes. And to that extent that they can't defend themselves at all. And this is an ideological

00:27:51.820 --> 00:27:57.180
[Guest 1]: question to answer. And I would say yes, we can differ on this plateau. But we should

00:27:57.180 --> 00:28:00.820
[Guest 1]: start thinking about it. If we were to do an Indian full ban, I would argue with you,

00:28:00.820 --> 00:28:06.340
[Guest 1]: then put the state capacity to take out the 6.1 crore guns which are unregistered. And

00:28:06.340 --> 00:28:10.060
[Guest 1]: what do you do with the guys who have registered guns? Manu Sharma shot somebody with a registered

00:28:10.060 --> 00:28:14.220
[Guest 1]: gun. Interestingly, it was registered with his father who was an MP probably. That's

00:28:14.220 --> 00:28:19.940
[Guest 1]: how he got a 22 caliber. And so the people who have registered guns, are we going to

00:28:19.940 --> 00:28:25.180
[Guest 1]: do a full blanket ban? I'm okay with a full blanket ban. But then no guns with cops, no

00:28:25.180 --> 00:28:30.140
[Guest 1]: exceptions to the ban by oh, you are in personal danger. So you can get a gun, go and get a

00:28:30.140 --> 00:28:33.900
[Guest 1]: security guard, pay for a cop to guard you.

00:28:33.900 --> 00:28:37.860
[Amit Varma]: But despite these statistics of how many guns we have and five for every hundred and so

00:28:37.860 --> 00:28:43.620
[Amit Varma]: on, would you broadly agree or disagree with the contention I made at the start of the

00:28:43.620 --> 00:28:48.620
[Amit Varma]: episode that we are in an equilibrium where nobody has guns, which seems broadly and again,

00:28:48.620 --> 00:28:52.580
[Amit Varma]: I'm obviously biased by my privileged existence in Bombay, where I don't see guns around me

00:28:52.580 --> 00:28:56.780
[Amit Varma]: at all and don't feel the need for one. And it's possible that in other parts of India,

00:28:56.780 --> 00:29:00.580
[Unknown]: it's obviously not like that and guns are a part of everyday violence and people are

00:29:00.580 --> 00:29:05.940
[Amit Varma]: defenseless against it. So is my contention about that equilibria false to begin with?

00:29:05.940 --> 00:29:09.540
[Guest 1]: I would say it is true for certain parts of India, but not true for large parts of India.

00:29:09.540 --> 00:29:14.500
[Guest 1]: If you go into the badlands of UP, Bihar, which is a border with Nepal, from where guns

00:29:14.500 --> 00:29:19.740
[Guest 1]: can come from China, if you go to Kashmir, where Pakistan has pumped guns into the system,

00:29:19.740 --> 00:29:27.460
[Guest 1]: if you go to Northeast, where again, the insurgencies have pumped guns from Myanmar, China, Bangladesh,

00:29:27.460 --> 00:29:32.420
[Guest 1]: that is not true. And there, I mean, because we have a single Indian Arms Act, all over

00:29:32.420 --> 00:29:39.100
[Guest 1]: the country, same law, that is you and I are beneficiaries of the equilibria here, but

00:29:39.100 --> 00:29:44.200
[Guest 1]: that reality is not the reality which a lot of people face. And that is something we should

00:29:44.200 --> 00:29:48.940
[Guest 1]: consider and point out and I'm okay for if you think of graded in terms of geography

00:29:48.940 --> 00:29:55.740
[Guest 1]: also. You can't have guns here, you can't have guns there. There are some problems with

00:29:55.740 --> 00:30:04.100
[Guest 1]: that also because people move freely. But it's not a reality of the system here. And

00:30:04.100 --> 00:30:08.460
[Guest 1]: the other question about the murder rate question, more than the absolute number and this is

00:30:08.460 --> 00:30:14.100
[Guest 1]: probably a very charged point, it's also important who gets killed. Okay, if murder rate goes

00:30:14.100 --> 00:30:18.220
[Guest 1]: up, but a few more bad people are getting killed, people who are threatening other people

00:30:18.220 --> 00:30:23.140
[Guest 1]: getting killed. Is that a horrible thing to be in?

00:30:23.140 --> 00:30:27.740
[Amit Varma]: I mean, if the data existed, I could consider that argument. But if it's a hypothetical

00:30:27.740 --> 00:30:33.300
[Amit Varma]: that you're proposing, then it's, you know, I wouldn't even know how to, like, I came

00:30:33.300 --> 00:30:38.800
[Amit Varma]: across some limited studies. And again, I haven't, to be very honest, I did the lazy

00:30:38.800 --> 00:30:43.620
[Amit Varma]: thing of just googling online for arguments against gun rights. I found some studies cited.

00:30:43.620 --> 00:30:48.480
[Amit Varma]: So I've just copy pasted the conclusions here. I haven't looked at the studies myself to

00:30:48.480 --> 00:30:50.340
[Amit Varma]: see the methodology as I would do.

00:30:50.340 --> 00:30:54.460
[Guest 1]: I've looked at one or two, there's another thing that happens. If you have relatively

00:30:54.460 --> 00:30:57.620
[Guest 1]: freer ownership of guns, violent break-ins fall.

00:30:57.620 --> 00:31:00.980
[Amit Varma]: Okay, because it might be the chance that the house owner has a gun and you could...

00:31:00.980 --> 00:31:06.620
[Guest 1]: And this has been studied when looking at smaller communities in the US with freer gun

00:31:06.620 --> 00:31:07.620
[Amit Varma]: rights and...

00:31:07.620 --> 00:31:11.100
[Amit Varma]: This is interesting. So what you're saying is you're changing the incentives for criminals

00:31:11.100 --> 00:31:15.260
[Amit Varma]: because they don't know who might fight back. And also you're changing the incentives for

00:31:15.260 --> 00:31:18.260
[Amit Varma]: even terrorists for something like the 2008 attacks.

00:31:18.260 --> 00:31:22.420
[Guest 1]: Yeah, I would say terrorist is difficult. Like if you have committed to kill yourself,

00:31:22.420 --> 00:31:26.140
[Guest 1]: you will do it, you will do it. And it will be only if somebody has a gun, they'll take

00:31:26.140 --> 00:31:30.580
[Guest 1]: you down. And hopefully that is this outcome you get. But yes, there is a lot of petty

00:31:30.580 --> 00:31:35.100
[Guest 1]: crime or petty violence that happens in India. I would call it petty because in the sense

00:31:35.100 --> 00:31:41.060
[Guest 1]: that the person who's doing it is in larger numbers to the victim and is just, you know,

00:31:41.060 --> 00:31:46.700
[Guest 1]: taking advantage of his size or numbers, lynchings, breaking-ins, things like that, where the

00:31:46.700 --> 00:31:51.300
[Guest 1]: person is just knows the other person is weak. And there I think gun changes that dynamic.

