00:47:28.620 --> 00:47:32.260
[Guest 1]: these strict gun laws. And again, therefore, I was also pointing out, if you have different

00:47:32.260 --> 00:47:37.220
[Guest 1]: gun laws across this country, we have to start thinking of some common minimum ones. Because

00:47:37.220 --> 00:47:41.580
[Guest 1]: otherwise you will create these incentives. And these incentives play out very easily.

00:47:41.580 --> 00:47:45.780
[Guest 1]: We think, oh, we have banned guns on metros. Therefore, we have made metro safe. Yes, you

00:47:45.780 --> 00:47:51.020
[Guest 1]: have made metro safe. But you have made the walk from the metro to the home very unsafe.

00:47:51.020 --> 00:47:56.900
[Guest 1]: And this there's no this one to one correlation between the law and the outcome you will get.

00:47:56.900 --> 00:48:02.300
[Guest 1]: You will get weird outcomes because people are game theory animals. And it creates these

00:48:02.300 --> 00:48:06.020
[Guest 1]: weird situations. So Chicago is a very interesting situation. If you read the law, you realize,

00:48:06.020 --> 00:48:12.260
[Guest 1]: oh, oh my god, if you're a complying citizen, and you have to really have a normal life,

00:48:12.260 --> 00:48:13.260
[Guest 1]: you can't carry a gun.

00:48:13.260 --> 00:48:18.100
[Amit Varma]: That's a great point. So now, both of you actually don't agree on this because Shubho

00:48:18.100 --> 00:48:22.420
[Amit Varma]: says that there should be like your view, therefore, it would be that if the citizen

00:48:22.420 --> 00:48:27.020
[Amit Varma]: needs correctly from monks, as I'm sure if I'm stating this, not quite accurately, but

00:48:27.020 --> 00:48:30.740
[Amit Varma]: what I understand of your view is that look, the citizen has a right to defend himself

00:48:30.740 --> 00:48:37.580
[Amit Varma]: from the state, as well as others. And therefore, it is perverse for the state to control the

00:48:37.580 --> 00:48:40.500
[Guest 2]: means of this defense by having licensing and so on.

00:48:40.500 --> 00:48:44.900
[Guest 2]: Yes, that would be one of my argument. Also, I would like to point out on the question

00:48:44.900 --> 00:48:50.460
[Guest 2]: of statistics. So when we were discussing a statistic earlier, it's very easy to get

00:48:50.460 --> 00:48:55.060
[Guest 2]: statistics on how many mass shootings and how many people are killed. But what is statistics

00:48:55.060 --> 00:49:00.260
[Guest 2]: you can't get on how many people were saved because of guns. So let's say a person comes

00:49:00.260 --> 00:49:05.780
[Guest 2]: to me with the intention of robbing me, I pull out my gun. Now I'm not going and that

00:49:05.780 --> 00:49:10.540
[Guest 2]: person runs away. I'm not going to go to the police and report this crime. It's not even

00:49:10.540 --> 00:49:15.580
[Guest 2]: a crime because it didn't happen to begin with. Now, how many people are defended like

00:49:15.580 --> 00:49:24.380
[Guest 2]: that every day? We don't know. And that hypothetical, we have instances where sometimes this mass

00:49:24.380 --> 00:49:30.780
[Guest 2]: shooters are shot by a person who had a gun legally. But we cannot get that statistics

00:49:30.780 --> 00:49:35.460
[Guest 2]: on how many people were saved. Millions and millions of them every day. And if you're

00:49:35.460 --> 00:49:43.220
[Guest 2]: in a country like in Latin America and Brazil and Chile or Honduras, you have to have a

00:49:43.220 --> 00:49:49.020
[Guest 2]: gun because otherwise the state has no capacity to defend you. Same in India. If I'm being

00:49:49.020 --> 00:49:53.580
[Guest 2]: robbed, the government is not going to defend me. As our friend points out, a gun in hand

00:49:53.580 --> 00:50:01.420
[Guest 2]: is much better than a cop on the phone. So yeah, but yeah, that is correct position that

00:50:01.420 --> 00:50:07.260
[Guest 2]: I want individuals to be able to defend themselves against the state, regardless of time and

00:50:07.260 --> 00:50:13.980
[Guest 2]: place and whatever. And I do not see any reason why that kind of restriction should agree,

00:50:13.980 --> 00:50:19.060
[Guest 2]: especially given the evidence that in the 19th century alone, we have 100 million people

00:50:19.060 --> 00:50:20.940
[Amit Varma]: killed by the state.

00:50:20.940 --> 00:50:24.860
[Amit Varma]: That's a fair point. But you know, I get the point about we don't know the counterfactuals

00:50:24.860 --> 00:50:28.380
[Amit Varma]: of you know, if you defended yourself against a robbery and the guy ran away, we don't know

00:50:28.380 --> 00:50:33.500
[Amit Varma]: the good that the possession of guns did. But what we do know is that we can look at

00:50:33.500 --> 00:50:37.900
[Amit Varma]: a few cases, for example, you can look at Australia, which changed his gun laws and

00:50:37.900 --> 00:50:42.780
[Amit Varma]: you can look at the crime rates before and after that. And obviously, the the rates that

00:50:42.780 --> 00:50:47.900
[Amit Varma]: I just quoted were only of gun related deaths, not deaths overall. So it's not the full picture.

00:50:47.900 --> 00:50:53.860
[Amit Varma]: But but one can look at data like that and come to some understanding maybe the US states

00:50:53.860 --> 00:50:58.340
[Amit Varma]: which have different laws are a kind of sort of natural experiment by itself. Is that so

00:50:58.340 --> 00:51:03.940
[Guest 1]: Yeah, so home breaking rates go down. Yeah, that's NRS favorite one. But yeah, it's a

00:51:03.940 --> 00:51:08.780
[Guest 1]: tough statistic to counter. Yeah. And it's also a much more personal point. Like if you

00:51:08.780 --> 00:51:15.980
[Guest 1]: break into my home, that is a violation, which is far more, you know, stronger as a violation

00:51:15.980 --> 00:51:20.900
[Guest 1]: that that you know, if you if you have returned to a home that has been broken in, it is such

00:51:20.900 --> 00:51:27.620
[Guest 1]: a shock. So it is I have not been victims of crime that much, but one small theft at

00:51:27.620 --> 00:51:30.780
[Guest 1]: my home for a little because the door was left unlocked by mistake, but it was such

00:51:30.780 --> 00:51:36.500
[Guest 1]: a shock. They took away some like broken microwave, which was not working. No monetary loss, but

00:51:36.500 --> 00:51:41.940
[Guest 1]: it was such a shock. You get this thing that this is my home, my castle, violated, violated.

00:51:41.940 --> 00:51:45.020
[Guest 1]: And that is a situation which goes down a lot.

00:51:45.020 --> 00:51:49.620
[Amit Varma]: So I'll come back to you for a moment, Shubham, because I want to sort of understand your

00:51:49.620 --> 00:51:54.500
[Amit Varma]: argument bit better. So Langshu's argument, in a sense is simple to understand, because

00:51:54.500 --> 00:51:57.860
[Amit Varma]: he's saying, I don't care about the consequences. I just care about first principles. And these

00:51:57.860 --> 00:52:01.220
[Amit Varma]: are my first principles. And so I'm saying that individuals should have the right to

00:52:01.220 --> 00:52:06.980
[Amit Varma]: protect yourself. Now, while you agree that it is hard to take a consequentialist position

00:52:06.980 --> 00:52:11.580
[Amit Varma]: on this, because the data is quite muddy, and all of that, at the same time, you're

00:52:11.580 --> 00:52:16.660
[Amit Varma]: not quite coming from first principles, because you are arguing that the state should have

00:52:16.660 --> 00:52:20.460
[Amit Varma]: gradations of licensing and all of this. So, you know,

00:52:20.460 --> 00:52:26.140
[Guest 1]: My point is that even when I come from first principles, you shouldn't, I come from first

00:52:26.140 --> 00:52:32.620
[Guest 1]: principles, not first principle. And I would say liberty is one of the principles. But

00:52:32.620 --> 00:52:37.100
[Guest 1]: there is also that we live in a society, we will have to manage our differences in society,

00:52:37.100 --> 00:52:43.020
[Guest 1]: we have to create disincentives to use violence as the first resort, or extreme violence as

00:52:43.020 --> 00:52:48.620
[Guest 1]: the bomb Zuka case in the first resort. So we'll have to come across these are two contradictory

00:52:48.620 --> 00:52:53.660
[Guest 1]: principles that I want maximum liberty. But I also don't want to, you know, live on a

00:52:53.660 --> 00:53:01.340
[Guest 1]: hill, 20 kilometers away, depending on the range of your bombs, look away from everybody

00:53:01.340 --> 00:53:07.380
[Guest 1]: else. That is not a good life. I love urban living. I love the fact that we can drop into

00:53:07.380 --> 00:53:12.660
[Guest 1]: a meeting and all of that and the bomb Zuka kind of makes it impossible if there's freely

00:53:12.660 --> 00:53:17.620
[Guest 1]: owned bomb Zuka because somebody having a bad day, as you pointed out, there are suicides,

00:53:17.620 --> 00:53:23.580
[Guest 1]: somebody having a bad day may decide not only will I go, I'll go with everybody around me.

00:53:23.580 --> 00:53:28.340
[Guest 1]: That is a very dangerous situation where I go. So I think that is where my principle

00:53:28.340 --> 00:53:36.380
[Guest 1]: is. But Sudhanshu's point about the state going crazy, there I would say that even if

00:53:36.380 --> 00:53:41.580
[Guest 1]: you have registration, if there are substantial number of guns, taking it away is difficult.

00:53:41.580 --> 00:53:46.340
[Guest 1]: Today, for example, it is very easy to take away guns, the registered guns, because 97

00:53:46.340 --> 00:53:51.860
[Guest 1]: percent of the people have guns, it is okay to take away. But it is infeasible for the

00:53:51.860 --> 00:53:55.940
[Guest 1]: government, for example, to take away all the cars in Delhi also. Where will you store

00:53:55.940 --> 00:54:00.620
[Guest 1]: the cars? There's so many cars. So I think if you have reached a level of ownership,

00:54:00.620 --> 00:54:06.500
[Guest 1]: which is quite high, then even if the government knows that these people have guns, you still

00:54:06.500 --> 00:54:13.060
[Guest 1]: have to come and take it away from me. And that becomes difficult. And I think once that

00:54:13.060 --> 00:54:18.820
[Guest 1]: has become a large enough population, I think what went wrong in Germany, in China, in Russia,

00:54:18.820 --> 00:54:23.900
[Guest 1]: also, I would say was not enough people had guns. So the few that had guns, the state

00:54:23.900 --> 00:54:28.780
[Guest 1]: had enough capacity to take it away. I would say, if a lot of people have simple weapons,

00:54:28.780 --> 00:54:33.380
[Guest 1]: and I don't think weapons of mass destruction or things like that, because you can't use

00:54:33.380 --> 00:54:37.500
[Guest 1]: them in an urban setting anyway. So state also can't use it in an urban setting without

00:54:37.500 --> 00:54:42.540
[Guest 1]: setting of civil war and all of that, then it's okay, because still some cop has to come

00:54:42.540 --> 00:54:46.900
[Guest 1]: up and knock and say, I want to take away your gun. And then if they are doing to every

00:54:46.900 --> 00:54:52.740
[Guest 1]: household to your neighbour to you, then the question is, why? How are you doing it? And

00:54:52.740 --> 00:54:56.740
[Guest 1]: then it breaks out in the open. But if there are only one in 100 people or two in 100 people

00:54:56.740 --> 00:55:01.580
[Guest 1]: who have guns, that is the number that's possible because what is happening cop has come to

00:55:01.580 --> 00:55:06.140
[Guest 1]: somebody's house, but if you have to take away everybody's gun, then it becomes a higher

00:55:06.140 --> 00:55:14.940
[Guest 1]: barrier to that question of you know, state going awry and going bad. But by that time,

00:55:14.940 --> 00:55:19.220
[Guest 1]: I would say by the time things have rolled to that level, where state is now going to

00:55:19.220 --> 00:55:27.780
[Guest 1]: put people into concentration camps. Guns are not the only defence against it. I think

00:55:27.780 --> 00:55:33.260
[Guest 1]: establishing rule of law, establishing democracy, those are hard work. And I think in some ways,

00:55:33.260 --> 00:55:37.380
[Guest 1]: I fear that we might become lazy about that then. Because we have guns, we don't take

00:55:37.380 --> 00:55:42.940
[Guest 1]: interest in the state. Okay, that is a counterfactual, I would think or hypothetical, we have to

00:55:42.940 --> 00:55:48.580
[Guest 1]: think about it, we have to, the price of liberty is eternal vigilance. So we'd have to be vigilant

00:55:48.580 --> 00:55:53.860
[Guest 1]: at all levels. So whenever a gun legislation is issued, or any other legislation is issued,

00:55:53.860 --> 00:55:58.700
[Guest 1]: like the debate that we had about the terrorism law, or any of these other laws, those are

00:55:58.700 --> 00:56:03.700
[Guest 1]: the things we should work towards to keep the state in check. By the time you have left

00:56:03.700 --> 00:56:09.940
[Guest 1]: it to the level that Hitler is, things are doing or by the time Pol Pot has come, things

00:56:09.940 --> 00:56:16.100
[Guest 1]: have gone too far. And I think there, the United Nations system is a little better.

00:56:16.100 --> 00:56:21.500
[Guest 1]: We have now a system of crime of genocide where other countries come and intervene.

00:56:21.500 --> 00:56:25.020
[Guest 1]: Though defective, I think it was not there in the First World War, it was after First

00:56:25.020 --> 00:56:29.340
[Guest 1]: World War, it was not there. Because after Second World War, we realized the problem

00:56:29.340 --> 00:56:35.460
[Guest 1]: and there is some level of pressure not to do that from the states and other states have

00:56:35.460 --> 00:56:40.900
[Guest 1]: to come together to prevent one state from going really rogue on its citizens. But yes,

00:56:40.900 --> 00:56:44.820
[Guest 1]: so I think two counters to that one is let's have enough guns so that it becomes infeasible

00:56:44.820 --> 00:56:49.260
[Guest 1]: for a state to collect back all of them. But yes, if you kill somebody, I should be able

00:56:49.260 --> 00:56:53.220
[Guest 1]: to trace where it came from. I don't want to live in a world where the state can raise

00:56:53.220 --> 00:56:56.300
[Guest 1]: up its arms and say, I don't know who killed it. Just like if a car hits and I have the

00:56:56.300 --> 00:57:01.660
[Guest 1]: number plate and you can't find the number, the owner of the car. That is not a level

00:57:01.660 --> 00:57:07.820
[Guest 1]: of freedom I want to give because I'm balancing multiple values and multiple first principles.

00:57:07.820 --> 00:57:12.420
[Amit Varma]: So Sudhanshu, I have a critical question of my own. But first, I'd like you to respond

00:57:12.420 --> 00:57:17.540
[Amit Varma]: to Shubho's implication that you are giving undue primacy to one first principle, that

00:57:17.540 --> 00:57:23.300
[Amit Varma]: of liberty, and not considering the other things that we should value and balance that

00:57:23.300 --> 00:57:24.300
[Amit Varma]: against.

00:57:24.300 --> 00:57:32.340
[Guest 2]: Okay, so, yes, I personally give most amount of value to first principles, that is liberty.

00:57:32.340 --> 00:57:37.580
[Guest 2]: Second on the question of large enough number of guns. I would like to point out the Japanese

00:57:37.580 --> 00:57:44.300
[Guest 2]: were interned in US and they had a large enough number of guns and had the right for hundreds

00:57:44.300 --> 00:57:50.580
[Guest 2]: of years at that point in time. Plus, the question of that state will go gradually from

00:57:50.580 --> 00:57:57.260
[Guest 2]: one point to another. I don't think that that is how it works. Indira Gandhi, the judgment

00:57:57.260 --> 00:58:01.860
[Guest 2]: was announced against her at maybe in the afternoon, two, three o'clock. By midnight,

00:58:01.860 --> 00:58:07.780
[Guest 2]: we had emergency on that day. And we live under the same constitution. We live under

00:58:07.780 --> 00:58:14.420
[Guest 2]: the same government. And we never know. I mean, as recently, government has said 28,000

00:58:14.420 --> 00:58:16.740
[Guest 2]: troops plus in Kashmir.

00:58:16.740 --> 00:58:20.860
[Amit Varma]: We're recording this on August 5, but the episode will be released much later. But we're

00:58:20.860 --> 00:58:23.540
[Guest 2]: recording this on August 5, just for context.

00:58:23.540 --> 00:58:29.740
[Guest 2]: So you never know how much a state will, a state will never go gradually that you know,

00:58:29.740 --> 00:58:35.660
[Guest 2]: we are going to come for you. And we know this many of you have guns, and we'll send

00:58:35.660 --> 00:58:40.900
[Guest 2]: this many people to that is not how it's going to happen. It is going to happen in a moment,

00:58:40.900 --> 00:58:45.220
[Guest 2]: in a friction of a second, somebody like Indira Gandhi will rise up and say the country is

00:58:45.220 --> 00:58:51.380
[Guest 2]: now under emergency, your fundamental rights are suspended. Your right to life also does

00:58:51.380 --> 00:58:58.260
[Guest 2]: not exist to begin with. And we have instances where Supreme Court has gone on to the extent

00:58:58.260 --> 00:59:04.440
[Guest 2]: of saying that yes, when you are killed under emergency, you have no right to life at all.

00:59:04.440 --> 00:59:09.900
[Guest 2]: And you have no remedy whatsoever. Now that situation is somewhat corrected. But that

00:59:09.900 --> 00:59:16.100
[Guest 2]: is not if the government has large enough majority, as the present government has, or

00:59:16.100 --> 00:59:20.340
[Guest 2]: any future government may have, everything is possible in this country and any other

00:59:20.340 --> 00:59:22.180
[Guest 2]: country whatsoever.

00:59:22.180 --> 00:59:29.300
[Guest 2]: So just thinking that if people had large enough number of guns, and we have instances

00:59:29.300 --> 00:59:35.740
[Guest 2]: in US where the military has fought civilians on US soil with large enough number of guns

00:59:35.740 --> 00:59:43.420
[Guest 2]: and killed maybe 2000 of them. We have had multiple such instances, not just one or two.

00:59:43.420 --> 00:59:52.700
[Guest 2]: So in, I think in the 70s, militia formed to 3000 people in Midwestern US and they were

00:59:52.700 --> 00:59:57.900
[Guest 2]: trying to run a campaign against the federal government in US. The US government just sent

00:59:57.900 --> 01:00:04.380
[Guest 2]: army military to deal with them. And they of course had higher grade weapons. Thousands

01:00:04.380 --> 01:00:10.860
[Guest 2]: were killed. And that effectively nullifies the argument that once a large enough number

01:00:10.860 --> 01:00:14.820
[Guest 2]: of people have guns, that is not how it's going to work because the state will always

01:00:14.820 --> 01:00:19.780
[Guest 2]: have more capacity than an individual, especially when it comes to violence.

01:00:19.780 --> 01:00:21.620
[Guest 2]: So in which case, why bother at all?

01:00:21.620 --> 01:00:23.820
[Guest 2]: Exactly. That's what I'm saying.

01:00:23.820 --> 01:00:29.380
[Guest 1]: So I think there again, if everyone has guns, then the paranoia of the state may also lead

01:00:29.380 --> 01:00:35.180
[Guest 1]: to disorder. That let's say everybody has bomb zookas. I have a fear that 28,000 troops

01:00:35.180 --> 01:00:40.900
[Guest 1]: have been sent to Kashmir and everybody in Kashmir explores their bomb zookas. End game

01:00:40.900 --> 01:00:44.740
[Guest 1]: for everybody. The problem with that level of mass destruction is that you create these

01:00:44.740 --> 01:00:52.060
[Guest 1]: end game situations where you can't walk back from or deescalate from because of that level

01:00:52.060 --> 01:00:57.420
[Guest 1]: of weapons of mass destruction being available in citizens hand because today, any nuclear

01:00:57.420 --> 01:01:02.300
[Guest 1]: weapon or something goes through multiple filter before somebody even to that extent,

01:01:02.300 --> 01:01:05.940
[Guest 1]: again, countering my own point. Yes, there are weapons of mass destruction in the hands

01:01:05.940 --> 01:01:10.180
[Guest 1]: of individual citizens in the army. But they have been trained, there's a protocol, there's

01:01:10.180 --> 01:01:14.260
[Guest 1]: a way to launch them. That gives a lot of time to think about launching weapons of mass

01:01:14.260 --> 01:01:19.100
[Guest 1]: destruction. So I think that is how weapons of mass destruction should be used. They should

01:01:19.100 --> 01:01:24.140
[Guest 1]: be used as deterrent and there should be protocols and systems. If it is in the hands of citizens,

01:01:24.140 --> 01:01:29.460
[Guest 1]: sadly, that structure collapses that. So I might panic one day, I might think the world

01:01:29.460 --> 01:01:34.180
[Guest 1]: is coming to an end, which happens a lot of times people start thinking you get cults

01:01:34.180 --> 01:01:38.140
[Guest 1]: who commit mass suicide. Now if they get bomb zookas, they want to take the entire town

01:01:38.140 --> 01:01:43.620
[Guest 1]: or city with them. That is a problem. So that is the extent I would go. But on the point

01:01:43.620 --> 01:01:52.220
[Guest 1]: of Indira Gandhi, I think there was science. I think if you read history back, she started

01:01:52.220 --> 01:01:57.580
[Guest 1]: encroaching rights from the 60s. You know, 69 she nationalized banks, she did a lot of

01:01:57.580 --> 01:02:06.660
[Guest 1]: nationalizations. She was doing extreme taxation. I mean, looking back, was 77 that big a surprise?

01:02:06.660 --> 01:02:08.220
[Amit Varma]: I don't think so. I mean, hit level.

01:02:08.220 --> 01:02:13.620
[Amit Varma]: 75 rather, but that's kind of that's also the hindsight bias kicking in. Yes, I think

01:02:13.620 --> 01:02:18.980
[Amit Varma]: we also have to believe contemporary accounts where there are enough people who, you know,

01:02:18.980 --> 01:02:22.980
[Amit Varma]: would have seen the science but was still taken by surprise. And also the thing is,

01:02:22.980 --> 01:02:28.740
[Amit Varma]: every state is by its nature looking to consolidate power and oppressive to some extent or the

01:02:28.740 --> 01:02:31.700
[Amit Varma]: other. So if you want to look for science, you will always find science.

01:02:31.700 --> 01:02:36.540
[Guest 1]: Yeah. And then if you are fully armed, then any sign can be a trigger for you to correct.

01:02:36.540 --> 01:02:40.860
[Guest 2]: That is amazing. That is amazing. That's how we keep government in check. That's the situation

01:02:40.860 --> 01:02:45.220
[Guest 2]: when they would think twice before infringing on even the smallest shred of your liberty.

01:02:45.220 --> 01:02:49.740
[Amit Varma]: No, that's fair enough. But I am still worried by the fact that any random guy can take a

01:02:49.740 --> 01:02:53.940
[Amit Varma]: bomb Zuka and decide Kima subco legage on and precedent thousands of people die.

01:02:53.940 --> 01:02:58.580
[Guest 2]: 18 men, I'm sorry, a boy 18 mentally competent, as I said at the very beginning.

01:02:58.580 --> 01:03:01.300
[Guest 2]: Oh, but that's not a guarantee. That's it.

01:03:01.300 --> 01:03:06.620
[Guest 1]: There's no guarantee in life. No, but I would say no, but that was not in, you know, was

01:03:06.620 --> 01:03:11.860
[Guest 1]: not crazy. Hmm. And let's see, you were angry, you killed your wife. Now the cops are coming

01:03:11.860 --> 01:03:15.660
[Guest 1]: and you have a bomb Zuka. You're above 18. You are mentally competent. You're going to

01:03:15.660 --> 01:03:20.460
[Amit Varma]: press that button because you're going down anyway. Right? Yeah. So you'll be like, whatever,

01:03:20.460 --> 01:03:26.260
[Guest 2]: dude, and press the thing. But that would be a very drastic action to take. And I'm

01:03:26.260 --> 01:03:35.020
[Guest 2]: very sure all humans are, there may be some psychopathic, but all it takes is one, right?

01:03:35.020 --> 01:03:40.500
[Amit Varma]: Of course, but you're saying you don't care about possibility. You cannot infringe on

01:03:40.500 --> 01:03:46.580
[Guest 2]: my rights. That is my point that just because you have impulses doesn't mean the state can

01:03:46.580 --> 01:03:51.020
[Amit Varma]: take away my rights. Fair enough. Don't look at me like that. I have no impulses. I am

01:03:51.020 --> 01:03:55.300
[Amit Varma]: a gentle soul. So let me ask you the question that I was kind of saving for you. And this

01:03:55.300 --> 01:03:59.380
[Amit Varma]: is again, something that I'm thinking through and chewing because you know, I can come up

01:03:59.380 --> 01:04:04.500
[Amit Varma]: with objections to it myself. And it's just a tough question, which is this, that yes,

01:04:04.500 --> 01:04:09.700
[Amit Varma]: we have a right to defend ourselves. However, in our conception, the classical liberal conception,

01:04:09.700 --> 01:04:14.820
[Amit Varma]: which at least you and I share, the whole purpose of the state is to defend those rights.

01:04:14.820 --> 01:04:19.660
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, for that reason, we give it a monopoly on violence and give it the license

01:04:19.660 --> 01:04:25.780
[Amit Varma]: to do whatever it takes to defend those rights. Now, if in the interest of maintaining law

01:04:25.780 --> 01:04:30.900
[Amit Varma]: and order, and what I'm now going to say has to be taken with a lot of caveats, because

01:04:30.900 --> 01:04:36.980
[Amit Varma]: immediately slippery slopes form. But if then the state says that my job is to solely look

01:04:36.980 --> 01:04:40.380
[Amit Varma]: after the rights of my citizens, which no state ever will, the state basically wants

01:04:40.380 --> 01:04:44.940
[Amit Varma]: to rule you. But if a state is to say that my job is to solely look after the rights

01:04:44.940 --> 01:04:51.460
[Amit Varma]: of its citizens, and the hypothetical possession of bomb Zuccas in the general population could

01:04:51.460 --> 01:04:57.780
[Amit Varma]: endanger many of these lives, which I am supposed to be saving, then I should preemptively act

01:04:57.780 --> 01:05:01.900
[Amit Varma]: to protect the citizens I am supposed to protect and therefore I should bomb the banzooka.

01:05:01.900 --> 01:05:06.900
[Amit Varma]: Now, obviously, I know that this kind of preemptive rationale that I'm doing it for your own protection

01:05:06.900 --> 01:05:11.980
[Amit Varma]: can be and would be misused by the state. But leaving that aside, do you think there

01:05:11.980 --> 01:05:16.900
[Guest 2]: is some merit to it at all? There is I can see some merit, but then again, the question

01:05:16.900 --> 01:05:22.540
[Guest 2]: of where do you draw the line? Right, right. So UK, for example, as Shubham pointed out,

01:05:22.540 --> 01:05:28.940
[Guest 2]: Ratan has become the knife capital of the world. In 1953, in UK, they passed a law banning

01:05:28.940 --> 01:05:34.460
[Guest 2]: canning of knives in public which are longer than three inches. And it still goes on. So

01:05:34.460 --> 01:05:40.100
[Guest 2]: my problem is okay, fine, you want to ban it, ban it. There will be criminals who will

01:05:40.100 --> 01:05:44.540
[Guest 2]: obtain access to it anyway. Like, okay, it was illegal for North Korea to obtain nuclear

01:05:44.540 --> 01:05:50.180
[Amit Varma]: weapons or for Iran. They got it anyway. But should the state then have the right to act

01:05:50.180 --> 01:05:56.020
[Amit Varma]: preemptively to carry out its primary job of safeguarding the rights of its citizens?

01:05:56.020 --> 01:06:00.440
[Amit Varma]: And if a line has to be drawn, so it doesn't become a slippery slope? Where would that

01:06:00.440 --> 01:06:04.740
[Guest 2]: line be drawn? Like, what would the parameters be? That is my question. I don't want to draw

01:06:04.740 --> 01:06:10.180
[Guest 2]: any lines. But since you two are in favor of drawing lines, that answer should lie with

01:06:10.180 --> 01:06:21.620
[Guest 2]: you. That being said, I don't think that there is any legal mechanism you can envisage, which

01:06:21.620 --> 01:06:29.060
[Guest 2]: would ban criminals from owning guns. So you can have all possible mechanism as Shubham

01:06:29.060 --> 01:06:35.460
[Guest 2]: pointed out, we have 7 crore, 6 crore guns, and 97 lakhs are only legal. So you have this

01:06:35.460 --> 01:06:40.220
[Guest 2]: 5-6 crore guns, which are illegal, which are just floating around in India. And I as a

01:06:40.220 --> 01:06:46.220
[Guest 2]: law abiding citizen, am defenseless. And you have been very lucky that you have never faced

01:06:46.220 --> 01:06:49.740
[Guest 2]: that situation. I've been robbed on knife point in Pune.

01:06:49.740 --> 01:06:50.740
[Guest 2]: In Pune?

01:06:50.740 --> 01:06:55.540
[Guest 2]: Yes. And in Delhi, I feel very unsafe. Actually, some of my friends carry knives with them.

01:06:55.540 --> 01:06:56.540
[Amit Varma]: You know.

01:06:56.540 --> 01:07:02.740
[Amit Varma]: I know one of them. Yes. And otherwise completely sturdy, reliable citizen. But I feel safe

01:07:02.740 --> 01:07:09.500
[Guest 2]: with him. Exactly. In Delhi, I don't feel safe. I just don't. And Paharganj, I'm not

01:07:09.500 --> 01:07:14.300
[Guest 2]: going to roam around after 11 o'clock because I'm not, I'm defenseless. And I know the state

01:07:14.300 --> 01:07:16.160
[Amit Varma]: is not going to defend me at all.

01:07:16.160 --> 01:07:18.260
[Amit Varma]: And that's you. It's far worse for women.

01:07:18.260 --> 01:07:22.700
[Guest 2]: Yeah, exactly. And I wish every woman in Delhi has a gun.

01:07:22.700 --> 01:07:26.860
[Guest 1]: That brings to the other point. You can't go to the assistant of people being beaten

01:07:26.860 --> 01:07:28.820
[Guest 1]: up also in Delhi streets.

01:07:28.820 --> 01:07:31.100
[Amit Varma]: Because you have nothing. You'll just get beaten up.

01:07:31.100 --> 01:07:33.100
[Guest 2]: You might be added to the list of people.

01:07:33.100 --> 01:07:34.100
[Guest 2]: Yeah, and they will have guns.

01:07:34.100 --> 01:07:38.100
[Guest 1]: Or they may not have guns also. But you can't just draw a gun and say, people, let's calm

01:07:38.100 --> 01:07:45.340
[Guest 1]: down. Let the cops come and solve this out. Because you can't even say that much. When

01:07:45.340 --> 01:07:50.300
[Guest 1]: somebody is beating people, somebody is becoming a fight. And I think that is a thing which

01:07:50.300 --> 01:07:56.740
[Guest 1]: is, for example, that to pass a law to give legal immunity to people who pick up strangers

01:07:56.740 --> 01:08:00.660
[Guest 1]: on the road who have been victims of roadside assistance, because you would get harassed

01:08:00.660 --> 01:08:03.580
[Amit Varma]: by the cops when you brought somebody to the hospital.

01:08:03.580 --> 01:08:07.060
[Amit Varma]: The incentives are horrible. And many people still don't know that the law has changed.

01:08:07.060 --> 01:08:08.060
[Guest 1]: So they're still hesitant to help others.

01:08:08.060 --> 01:08:11.260
[Guest 1]: Even the cops don't know the law has changed. The cops will continue to harass you. So that

01:08:11.260 --> 01:08:15.780
[Guest 1]: is an issue that we have. And that is also something we should think about it. But to

01:08:15.780 --> 01:08:20.140
[Guest 1]: your point about Bomzuka and Sudhanshu's point there, I would say that is a problem of the

01:08:20.140 --> 01:08:25.100
[Guest 1]: 20th century. I would say till before the 20th century, you could not really take out

01:08:25.100 --> 01:08:32.580
[Guest 1]: percentages of the population of your city or of your country. You know, so as I see

01:08:32.580 --> 01:08:39.660
[Guest 1]: individual person, you could not. I mean, with the birth of new clear weapons, poisonous,

01:08:39.660 --> 01:08:47.340
[Guest 1]: I mean, neurotoxin type, the VX poison, chemical weapons and biological weapons, now, an individual

01:08:47.340 --> 01:08:54.180
[Guest 1]: can take out half of the world or all of the world. And this is a problem. And this did

01:08:54.180 --> 01:08:59.780
[Guest 1]: not exist. And my experience from law is that law takes around 300 years to solve a problem.

01:08:59.780 --> 01:09:05.660
[Guest 1]: That's the fastest law works. Look, how long did it take us to find out that everybody

01:09:05.660 --> 01:09:11.140
[Guest 1]: should get a right to vote? Okay, it took us 20,000 years of civilization, I would say,

01:09:11.140 --> 01:09:16.380
[Guest 1]: to come to democracy, pretty still pretty bad at working. So my rough estimate is it

01:09:16.380 --> 01:09:21.660
[Guest 1]: takes about 300 years for law to come to a conclusion about that part. So I think weapons

01:09:21.660 --> 01:09:26.740
[Guest 1]: of mass destruction are just too early for us to wrap our head around and solve it. I

01:09:26.740 --> 01:09:32.340
[Guest 1]: think we are doing very good at it. We have only used them twice. 50 years, we haven't

01:09:32.340 --> 01:09:37.180
[Guest 1]: used them quite surprising. But it seems there's some sense prevailing. I mean, I suspect Sadangshu

01:09:37.180 --> 01:09:43.900
[Amit Varma]: would say that that is an argument for deterrence. And that is what but deterrence can work between

01:09:43.900 --> 01:09:48.340
[Amit Varma]: states which are by and large rational actors. If you give every human being a bomb Zuka,

01:09:48.340 --> 01:09:52.180
[Amit Varma]: I don't know what role deterrence plays there. Some nutcase is going to say

01:09:52.180 --> 01:09:59.460
[Guest 2]: Sanyam Bhutani Of course, that and that is the risk we have to bear. That's I mean, there's

01:09:59.460 --> 01:10:03.940
[Guest 2]: no other way. Do you want to draw a line, then show me where you will draw the line

01:10:03.940 --> 01:10:09.380
[Guest 2]: and for what reasons, then I might be able to agree with you. As far as I see, I don't

01:10:09.380 --> 01:10:14.500
[Guest 2]: see why you should not draw a line at let's say matchstick because I could basically set

01:10:14.500 --> 01:10:20.180
[Guest 2]: this studio on fire right away. Are you going to ban matchsticks? Or are you going to ban

01:10:20.180 --> 01:10:21.620
[Guest 2]: spoons because I'm getting fat?

01:10:21.620 --> 01:10:24.340
[Amit Varma]: Sanyam Bhutani That's that's a good point. Are you going

01:10:24.340 --> 01:10:28.460
[Amit Varma]: to ban sugar? No sugar is poison, but bloody hell people have a right to consume poison,

01:10:28.460 --> 01:10:34.100
[Amit Varma]: the classic libertarian position. So it's been really stimulating conversation for me

01:10:34.100 --> 01:10:37.900
[Amit Varma]: and I'm going to take time to process all of this. So I'm not going to say I've changed

01:10:37.900 --> 01:10:41.260
[Amit Varma]: my mind and you've convinced me and I can't even say that because you guys have actually

01:10:41.260 --> 01:10:46.780
[Amit Varma]: made slightly separate arguments. But I am I'm pretty sure Sudhanshu though I have to

01:10:46.780 --> 01:10:51.340
[Amit Varma]: say with great regret that I don't think I'll quite go on the line of the bomb Zucca being

01:10:51.340 --> 01:10:57.260
[Amit Varma]: available over the counter. But I might get myself to agree with Shubha but that could

01:10:57.260 --> 01:11:01.860
[Amit Varma]: be a failure of imagination on my part. My purpose for this episode really was we were

01:11:01.860 --> 01:11:05.740
[Amit Varma]: chatting over this at dinner the other night and I thought this is a very stimulating discussion.

01:11:05.740 --> 01:11:10.260
[Amit Varma]: I am being forced to reconsider some of my positions whether I change my mind or not.

01:11:10.260 --> 01:11:14.420
[Amit Varma]: Let's put these arguments out there on the table. The final question I'd asked before

01:11:14.420 --> 01:11:19.660
[Amit Varma]: I sort of ended is that are we discussing that in a utopian world, this should be what

01:11:19.660 --> 01:11:24.780
[Amit Varma]: the law should be like? Or are both of you saying that in India today as it is as things

01:11:24.780 --> 01:11:27.700
[Amit Varma]: stand, this is our position. This is what we should do.

01:11:27.700 --> 01:11:30.820
[Guest 2]: Sanyam Bhutani So I would say in a utopian world,

01:11:30.820 --> 01:11:33.140
[Amit Varma]: Sadhguru But I'm asking what the India of today.

01:11:33.140 --> 01:11:35.780
[Guest 2]: Sanyam Bhutani Okay. No, no, no. I'll come to both points

01:11:35.780 --> 01:11:39.820
[Guest 2]: actually. In a utopian world, yes, every adult should be able to have a gun whether they

01:11:39.820 --> 01:11:45.060
[Guest 2]: want it or not is their problem. Okay. In India, as things stand today, every adult

01:11:45.060 --> 01:11:51.980
[Guest 2]: should be able to get a gun because our state is incapable of protecting us. And there are

01:11:51.980 --> 01:11:58.100
[Guest 2]: already five, four, seven crores illegal guns roaming around. So I don't see how the number

01:11:58.100 --> 01:12:03.180
[Guest 2]: going maybe 15 crore or 20 crore is going to be a problem.

01:12:03.180 --> 01:12:05.580
[Amit Varma]: Sadhguru Right. So that's your position that you're

01:12:05.580 --> 01:12:09.380
[Amit Varma]: not talking about utopia. This is your position now. Shobha, what about you?

01:12:09.380 --> 01:12:12.540
[Guest 1]: Shobha So my position is again, if we do bans, we

01:12:12.540 --> 01:12:18.100
[Guest 1]: stop thinking about it. Yeah, we can't stop thinking about the citizens right to defend

01:12:18.100 --> 01:12:24.500
[Guest 1]: themselves out at all times. I'm not arguing for changing the law today. All I'm asking

01:12:24.500 --> 01:12:29.660
[Guest 1]: is the same point that lot more Indians to pay attention to the Arms Act to pay attention

01:12:29.660 --> 01:12:35.180
[Guest 1]: to the debate. And I'm okay with the democratic debate coming up with some solution. I am

01:12:35.180 --> 01:12:40.980
[Guest 1]: unhappy with the presumption that a lot of us Indian elites do that the current equilibrium

01:12:40.980 --> 01:12:45.700
[Guest 1]: is good and stable. I'm saying let's have a debate. Let's debate and maybe after a debate,

01:12:45.700 --> 01:12:50.660
[Guest 1]: we can come back to the same position. But let us have the debate and I would like that

01:12:50.660 --> 01:12:56.620
[Guest 1]: debate to be open all the time. Situation change before the Bombay attacks. I think

01:12:56.620 --> 01:13:01.340
[Guest 1]: that situation was different for urban elites, but it was very similar for Kashmiri victims

01:13:01.340 --> 01:13:07.420
[Guest 1]: and victims in Naxal prone areas. I think we should have this debate all the time. That

01:13:07.420 --> 01:13:11.780
[Guest 1]: is why we have a permanent legislature that we should have this debate and you know, we

01:13:11.780 --> 01:13:16.060
[Guest 1]: Indian elites have to carry this intellectualism on this. We can't say the person who says

01:13:16.060 --> 01:13:20.180
[Guest 1]: that no, the gun laws in India are bad to just close that debate and I'm thankful that

01:13:20.180 --> 01:13:23.380
[Guest 1]: you're opening the debate here and we'll get nuances.

01:13:23.380 --> 01:13:27.860
[Amit Varma]: And then my immediate response to that though I meant to end it but what can I do my overactive

01:13:27.860 --> 01:13:32.140
[Amit Varma]: brain keeps ticking and my immediate thought to that not a response not an argument against

01:13:32.140 --> 01:13:39.380
[Amit Varma]: it is that affairs in human life and even for states are driven largely by inertia,

01:13:39.380 --> 01:13:43.500
[Amit Varma]: that this is a law that exists is going to continue to exist unless there is a crisis

01:13:43.500 --> 01:13:48.060
[Amit Varma]: which will make people reconsider it. And the only kind of crisis that I can envisage

01:13:48.060 --> 01:13:53.100
[Amit Varma]: that will make people reconsider it is if the state is so oppressive that the need for

01:13:53.100 --> 01:13:57.900
[Amit Varma]: guns is so acutely felt that there is public demand for it which hasn't happened so far

01:13:57.900 --> 01:14:02.020
[Amit Varma]: in our history. But then if the state is so acutely oppressive, then there's no point

01:14:02.020 --> 01:14:07.660
[Guest 2]: to the public demand. So we kind of start I would argue the state is that kind of oppressive.

01:14:07.660 --> 01:14:13.220
[Amit Varma]: Maybe you don't feel it maybe maybe a Kashmiri feels it maybe you don't know I agree with

01:14:13.220 --> 01:14:19.620
[Amit Varma]: you and I feel that oppression is normalized, you know, so it is not that you know, one

01:14:19.620 --> 01:14:23.340
[Amit Varma]: of you made the point about how everything can change overnight. But I think that oppression

01:14:23.340 --> 01:14:28.540
[Amit Varma]: is normalized so much that we don't feel the need to resist. I knew you'd nod your head

01:14:28.540 --> 01:14:29.540
[Amit Varma]: at that.

01:14:29.540 --> 01:14:34.820
[Guest 1]: I look at it I see the defense against the state as a smaller debate in the gun issue.

01:14:34.820 --> 01:14:39.460
[Guest 1]: Okay, more against defense against other bad citizens, other individuals, other individuals.

01:14:39.460 --> 01:14:44.020
[Guest 1]: And there I think, see the fact that there are five crore unregistered guns is that if

01:14:44.020 --> 01:14:48.980
[Guest 1]: it is that some people are sold it amongst themselves without working about the democracy,

01:14:48.980 --> 01:14:55.700
[Guest 1]: but I think the role of elites in this country is, I would say magnified, we play a bigger

01:14:55.700 --> 01:14:59.540
[Guest 1]: role, we have to make sure the debate happens. And we have to make sure the debate happened.

01:14:59.540 --> 01:15:03.800
[Guest 1]: I don't agree with the way you're thinking about democracy that demand will come and

01:15:03.800 --> 01:15:10.440
[Guest 1]: only then the rational solution will come. It's the job of the elites to give good solutions.

01:15:10.440 --> 01:15:14.260
[Guest 1]: And to give good solutions, you have to be experts on the topic. And you have to start

01:15:14.260 --> 01:15:18.540
[Guest 1]: thinking about it. It's not my primary topic of interest or research, but we have to do

01:15:18.540 --> 01:15:22.380
[Guest 1]: these and keep debating them even if we are not changing any law. So at the time when

01:15:22.380 --> 01:15:27.180
[Guest 1]: we change laws, we don't go for some other extreme, like I would say, Sudan, choose extreme

01:15:27.180 --> 01:15:32.220
[Guest 1]: that you have to be you have to allow extreme weapons or we can have that debate and then

01:15:32.220 --> 01:15:36.660
[Guest 1]: let the democracy decide where we want to go about it.

01:15:36.660 --> 01:15:40.620
[Amit Varma]: And I'll end this episode with I mean, since you pointed out the distinction between self

01:15:40.620 --> 01:15:44.380
[Amit Varma]: defense against the state and self defense against others, I'll end this episode by plugging

01:15:44.380 --> 01:15:48.140
[Amit Varma]: an old episode of mine, which will be linked from the show notes, where the philosopher

01:15:48.140 --> 01:15:54.180
[Amit Varma]: Jason Brennan made an argument on the show that those rights should be exactly equivalent

01:15:54.180 --> 01:15:59.500
[Amit Varma]: in any situation where you have a right to defend yourself or others against private

01:15:59.500 --> 01:16:04.620
[Amit Varma]: individuals, you should have this exact same right with no added consideration to defend

01:16:04.620 --> 01:16:06.500
[Amit Varma]: yourself against the state.

01:16:06.500 --> 01:16:09.340
[Guest 2]: Shubham Sudhanshu, sorry, you want to add a point?

01:16:09.340 --> 01:16:16.620
[Guest 2]: I agree with that way of analysis. So I don't see how I can put a primacy over my defense

01:16:16.620 --> 01:16:21.060
[Guest 2]: against another individual or my defense against the state. I will treat them equally.

